1 Communication; and
2 WHEREAS, Allyce especially treasured her summer abroad in Germany and
3 developed a lifelong passion for history, delighting in learning about British history,
4 particularly the War of the Roses; and
5 WHEREAS, Allyce discovered her calling at the Louisiana State Capitol when she
6 delivered a speech raising awareness about dyslexia, a learning disability she tirelessly
7 managed, and in doing so became an avid reader who often could be found working through
8 two books at once; and
9 WHEREAS, Allyce went on to serve the people of Louisiana as a government
10 relations advisor at Adams & Reese, a position she considered her dream job and one she
11 approached with enthusiasm, professionalism, and heartfelt dedication; and
12 WHEREAS, her warmth, sincerity, and radiant smile endeared her to legislators,
13 staff, and colleagues throughout the capitol, where she was known for her kindness, work
14 ethic, and genuine love for public service; and
15 WHEREAS, she carried herself with an unwavering positivity and an upbeat spirit
16 that uplifted those around her, which served as a reminder that joy and kindness have a
17 powerful place even in the most demanding environments; and
18 WHEREAS, known for being both witty and effortlessly chic, Allyce brought a
19 distinctive grace and spark to every room she entered, combining sharp insight with a
20 lighthearted charm that made her presence unforgettable; and
21 WHEREAS, although the Louisiana State Capitol is often regarded as a serious place
22 of weighty decisions and long hours, Allyce had a remarkable ability to bring smiles to our
23 faces, brightening difficult days with laughter, encouragement, and her unmistakable light;
24 and
25 WHEREAS, outside of work, Allyce found joy in fishing in the gulf, exploring
26 museums, attending estate sales, playing with cats, savoring champagne and oysters, and
27 sharing sushi dinners with friends and family; and
28 WHEREAS, Allyce was a gifted conversationalist who made others feel seen and
29 valued, often sending handwritten letters sealed with wax and remembering every birthday
30 of those she loved with thoughtful gifts; and
